White Wine Quality by Kutay Erkan

In this report, we will try to explore a dataset with approximately 4900 observations about the attributes of white wine and its perceived quality.

  • Quality and X are integer variables.
  • Quality is the variable we will focus on the most. It is an integer (discrete) and categorical variable with values between 3 and 9. Its mean is 5.878 and median is 6.
  • X seems to be a numerical Unique Identifier Variable, as difference between consecutive variables is always 1.

Univariate Analysis

Transformations

When we look at our histograms, we see that following variables seem skewed: * fixed.acidity * volatile.acidity * citric.acid * free.sulfur.dioxide * total.sulfur.dioxide * sulphates * alcohol

When we research it, we learn that pH scale is approximately base 10 logarithm of hydrogen ions in a solution. Considering this fact and the tails, we will transform *.acidity variables using base 10 logarithm.

We get very normal distributions except for the tail of citric.acid, containing values lower than 0.1 g/dm^3.

Outliers

We use boxplots with an alpha value of 0.05 to see possible outliers in each of our datasets.

New (Created) Features

As quality variable is basically a measure of how good or bad a wine is, it is logical to convert it to a categorical variable. For this purpose we create a new variable called class. We can use class to separately inspect what is happening feature-wise in different types of wine (bad, good etc.).

While separating quality levels to create a class variable, at first I thought using 3 classes; bad, good, and average. But I decided against it as bundling quality levels 5 and 6 together would cause a huge fraction of data points to be in the same class. Thus it is decided to use four levels: A, B, C and D. Grouping can be seen below:

Quality Class
7, 8, 9, 10 A
6 B
5 C
1, 2, 3, 4 D

We already have a variable for pH, but when we already have 3 variables for acidity, we can assign a separate variable for acidity and use it as a feature.

Looking in the documentation, unit for all acidity variables are g/dm^3, so we can directly sum them.

Bivariate Plots Section

To get a quick snapshot of relationships between all the fatures, we look at their plot and correlation matrices:

When we look at the relationship between quality and other features, there is a strong relationship between quality and alcohol. Density is correlated with alcohol (inversely) and residual sugar, which is not surprising. We also see that quality is correlated with chlorides (salt), volatile acidity, and total sulfur dioxide; all of which will be examined further.

When we use jitter and transparency on the points we see alcohol has a significant positive effect on the quality.

While chlorides dont seem to break a wine in lower amounts, the fact that there is no wine with a quality of 6 or bigger when chloride (salt) amount is bigger than 0.2 g/dm^3 might indicate higher amounts of salt affects quality perception. Indeed, top notch wines (quality of 9) have lower than 0.05 g/dm^3.

Effect of volatile acidity on quality is not exactly clear, and should be further investigated later on.

Even though we remove outliers of bottom and top by 5%, theres no significant change on quality created by different sulfur dioxide amounts.

Bivariate Analysis

Other than obvious relationships between the ones like sulfur.dioxides or acidities; strongest relationships are between density - alcohol, density - residual sugar, and quality - alcohol. It is also interesting that fixed acidity has a 0.99 correlation with acidity, suggesting fixed acids are in much higher concentrations in the wines.

Multivariate Plots Section

we use the classes we created to differentiate points, and apply upper 95% quantile on chlorides.

We see in the documentation that volatile acidity is acetic acid. If a wine has both low alcohol and high acetic acid, it tends to have worse quality.

Multivariate Analysis

We see that alcohol is indeed very important in the perceived quality of a wine. Having a high salt concentration affects it badly, and other chemicals such as volatile acids and sulfur dioxide shouldnt be higher than a certain amount.

Plot One

Description One

This is the first clear indicator we have regarding the relationship between alcohol content and perceived quality of a white wine.

Plot Two

Description Two

We see that Class A and B wines mostly reside in the lower right corner while lower quality wines are generally in upper left corner. In addition to alcohol, we see that high amount of salt might affect a wines quality badly.

Plot Three

Description Three

Finally, we also see acetic acid affecting the quality of a wine in addition to alcohol. Note the log10 transformation, used as volatile.acidity variable a form close to normal when transformed, and it is naturally a logarithmic variable.

Reflection

Main struggle for me was having an integer variable (quality) to investigate other features effects on. It required more technical additions, like converting it to a ordinal variable. Also not having much of an intutition regarding which material(s) make a wine better prompted me to make extra research. Seeing how alcohol played a part in wine quality also surprised me. A point going forward could be using a mathematical model to test if the mentioned relationships are there, and can such models predict quality of a wine without no one testing it.
